Question 1.

Most of the questions below use the dataset dataSet1.csv. In most cases, answering the questions will be easiest if the data is converted to a tidy format. Convert dataSet1.csv to a tidy format and print the first 10 rows. Rename the two columns to be Group and Score.

Click for Solution 
# Note that there are many ways to do this
library(tidyverse)
data <- read_csv("dataSet1.csv")

# Reshaping the data
data_tidy <- pivot_longer(
  data,
  cols = 1:length(data),

Question 2.

For each column in dataSet1.csv calculate the mean, variance, and standard deviation for both populations and samples. Dont use the mean(), var(), or sd() functions.

  • Hint: there are two ways to go about this: The long laborious way and the shorter convenient way. Which will you choose?
Click for Solution 
# Get Stats
results <- data_tidy |>
  group_by(Group) |>
  summarise(
    n = length(Score),
    m = sum(Score) / n,
    pop_var = sum((Score - m)^2) / (n),
    samp_var = sum((Score - m)^2) / (n - 1),
    pop_sd = sqrt(sum((Score - m)^2) / (n)),
    samp_sd = sqrt(sum((Score - m)^2) / (n - 1))
  )

Question 3.

Plot histograms of each column in dataSet1.csv. (Hint this is really easy if youve tidied up your data).

Click for Solution 
ggplot(data_tidy, aes(x = Score)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 15, fill = "#BB2528", colour = "black") +
  facet_wrap(~Group, scales = "free", nrow = 2) +
  xlab("Score") +
  ylab("Count")

  • Note: The argument scales = "free" tells ggplot to allow the x and y axis scales to vary across the facets. Functionality like this is why ggplot is so useful. Imagine trying to create an equivalent plot in Microsoft Excel (*shudders*).

Question 6.

Transform the skewed columns in dataSet1.csv to make them as normal looking as possible. Plot them as a density plot. Report the value of Tukeys lambda you used for each.

  • Note: if there are negative values in the data, you should probably figure out a simple way to remove them, otherwise you might have difficulty transforming your data.


Column Cs Data

Click for Solution 
library(rcompanion)

# Get smallest value
min(data$C)
## [1] -2.505994
# Since the smallest value is -2.5 I will add 3 to all the values when I
# calculate lambda and plot the data.  This is to prevent negatives and zeros.
lambdaC <- transformTukey((data$C + 3),
  plotit = FALSE,
  returnLambda = TRUE,
  quiet = TRUE
)

# Plot
ggplot(data, aes(x = (C + 3)^lambdaC)) +
  geom_density(fill = "#2297E6", linewidth = 1, colour = "black") +
  xlab(bquote(~ (Score + 3)^.(lambdaC))) +
  ylab("Density")

Question 7.

For each column, A - D, in dataSet1.csv, test the hypotheses that \(H_0: \mu_0 = -0.833\). For the remaining columns, E - H, test \(H_0: \mu_0 > -0.833\).

  • Set \(\alpha = 0.01\).
  • Test using both a classic t-test and a trimmed t-test with 20% trimming.
  • You are not allowed to use the function t.test().
  • Report test-statistic, degrees of freedom, p-value, and confidence intervals.
  • Again, there is a fast way to do this, and a slow laborious way. Which will you choose?


Columns A - D Classic One-Sample T-Tests: \(H_0: \mu_0 = -0.833\)

Click for Solution 
# Separate Columns A-D (see note at bottom)
data_AD <- filter(data_tidy, Group %in% c("A", "B", "C", "D"))

# Use summarise() to run your t-tests and save yourself hours of typing
classic_AD <- data_AD |>
  group_by(Group) |>
  summarise(

    # Basic Stats
    mu = -0.833,
    alpha = 0.01,
    n = length(Score),
    m = mean(Score),
    se = sd(Score) / sqrt(n),

    # Degrees of Freedom
    df = n - 1,

    # Test Statistic and P-value
    t_stat = (m - mu) / se,
    p = pt(abs(t_stat), df = df, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2,

    # Confidence Intervals
    t_crit = abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df)),
    moe = t_crit * se,
    CI = paste(
      "[",
      round(m - moe, 3), ", ",
      round(m + moe, 3),
      "]",
      sep = ""
    )
  )

classic_AD |>
  select(Group, t_stat, df, p, CI)
## # A tibble: 4  5
##   Group t_stat    df         p CI              
##   <chr>  <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>           
## 1 A     12.31    199 2.993e-26 [0.503, 1.219]  
## 2 B     17.21    199 2.971e-41 [2.327, 3.452]  
## 3 C     -2.418   199 1.650e- 2 [-1.195, -0.82] 
## 4 D     -2.259   199 2.499e- 2 [-1.178, -0.809]
  • Note: %in% just identifies if a value is contained in a vector. In this case it returns TRUE when the value in the group column contains A, B, C, or D, and returns FALSE for anything else.


Columns A - D Trimmed One-Sample T-Tests: \(H_0: \mu_0 = -0.833\)

Click for Solution 
library(WRS2)

trim_AD <- data_AD |>
  group_by(Group) |>
  summarise(

    # Basic Stats
    alpha = 0.01,
    mu = -0.833,
    n = length(Score),

    # Trimmed mean and sd
    G = 0.20,
    m = mean(Score, tr = G),
    s = sqrt(winvar(Score, tr = G)),

    # Standard Error for Confidence Interval Calculation
    se = s / ((1 - 2 * G) * sqrt(n)),

    # Degrees of Freedom
    h = n - 2 * floor(G * n),
    df = h - 1,

    # Margin of Error for Confidence Interval
    t_crit = abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df)),
    moe = t_crit * se,

    # Test statistic and P-value
    t_stat = ((1 - 2 * G) * (m - mu)) / (s / sqrt(n)),
    p = pt(abs(t_stat), df = df, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2,

    # Confidence Interval
    CI = paste(
      "[",
      round(m - moe, 3), ", ",
      round(m + moe, 3),
      "]",
      sep = ""
    )
  )

trim_AD |>
  select(Group, t_stat, df, p, CI)
## # A tibble: 4  5
##   Group t_stat    df         p CI              
##   <chr>  <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl> <chr>           
## 1 A     12.56    119 1.514e-23 [0.471, 1.158]  
## 2 B     17.92    119 1.356e-35 [2.421, 3.534]  
## 3 C     -4.107   119 7.393e- 5 [-1.363, -0.95] 
## 4 D     -2.336   119 2.119e- 2 [-1.184, -0.813]

Question 9.

Using dataSet1.csv, run a classic two-sample t-test on the following compairisons and hypotheses:

  1. A vs B: \(H_0: \mu_A - \mu_B = 0\)
  2. E vs F: \(H_0: \mu_E - \mu_F = 0\)
  3. D vs F: \(H_0: \mu_D - \mu_F < 0\)
  4. G vs H: \(H_0: \mu_G - \mu_H < -0.11\)
  • Set \(\alpha = 0.05\).
  • Report the test-statistic, degrees of freedom, p-value, and a appropriate confidence interval on the difference, Cohens d and Hedges g.
  • Plot the means with two-sided 95% confidence intervals.
  • You are not allowed to use the functions t.test() or cohen.d().


1. A vs B: \(H_0: \mu_A - \mu_B = 0\)

Click for Solution 
n1 <- length(data$A)
n2 <- length(data$B)

# Pooled Variance
sp_sq <- ((n1 - 1) * var(data$A) + (n2 - 1) * var(data$B)) / (n1 + n2 - 2)

# Pooled Standard Error
se <- sqrt(sp_sq / n1 + sp_sq / n2)

# Test Statistic
mu <- 0
diff <- mean(data$A) - mean(data$B)
t_stat <- (diff - mu) / se

# Degrees of Freedom
df <- (n1 - 1) + (n2 - 1)

# p-value
p <- pt(abs(t_stat), df = df, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2

# Confidence Interval
alpha <- 0.05
t_crit <- abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df))

CI_bot <- diff - t_crit * se
CI_top <- diff + t_crit * se
CI <- paste("[", round(CI_bot, 3),
  ", ", round(CI_top, 3),
  "]",
  sep = ""
)

# Cohen's d
d <- diff / sqrt(sp_sq)

# Hedge's g
g <- d * (1 - (3 / (4 * (n1 + n2) - 9)))
## T = -7.913
## df = 398
## p = 2.517554e-14
## CI = [-2.533, -1.525]
## d = -0.791
## g = -0.79
# Subset values from tidy data
data_AB <- filter(data_tidy, Group == "A" | Group == "B")

# Use summarise() to compute everything I need for the plot
plot_data <- data_AB |>
  group_by(Group) |>
  summarise(
    n = length(Score),
    m = mean(Score),
    se = sd(Score) / sqrt(n),
    df = n - 1,
    alpha = 0.05,
    t_crit = abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df)),
    moe = t_crit * se
  )

# Plot
ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = Group, y = m)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", colour = "black", aes(fill = Group)) +
  geom_errorbar(
    aes(
      ymin = m - moe,
      ymax = m + moe
    ),
    width = 0.25
  ) +
  xlab("Group") +
  ylab("Score")

Question 10.

Repeat the previous question using a Welchs T-test. Dont bother plotting the means or calculating Cohens d and Hedges g.


1. A vs B: \(H_0: \mu_A - \mu_B = 0\)

Click for Solution 
n1 <- length(data$A)
n2 <- length(data$B)

var1 <- var(data$A)
var2 <- var(data$B)

# Standard Error of the Difference
se <- sqrt(var1 / n1 + var2 / n2)

# Test Statistic
mu <- 0
diff <- mean(data$A) - mean(data$B)
t_stat <- (diff - mu) / se

# Degrees of Freedom
q1 <- var1 / n1
q2 <- var2 / n2

df <- ((q1 + q2)^2) /
  (((q1^2) / (n1 - 1)) + ((q2^2) / (n2 - 1)))

# p-value
p <- pt(abs(t_stat), df = df, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2

# Confidence Interval
alpha <- 0.05
t_crit <- abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df))

CI_bot <- diff - t_crit * se
CI_top <- diff + t_crit * se
CI <- paste(
  "[",
  round(CI_bot, 3), ", ",
  round(CI_top, 3),
  "]",
  sep = ""
)
## T = -7.913
## df = 337.4244
## p = 3.642909e-14
## CI = [-2.533, -1.524]

Question 11.

Repeat the previous question using Trimmed T-tests with 20% trimming. For each, plot a bar graph of the means using two-sided 95% confidence intervals on the trimmed mean. You are not allowed to used yuen().

  • Note: if you use yuen() to check your answers you may need to factor your columns first. Also, yuen() only computes two-sided tests and does not allow you to specify \(\mu\).


1. A vs B: \(H_0: \mu_A - \mu_B = 0\)

Click for Solution 
n1 <- length(data$A)
n2 <- length(data$B)

# Trim Prop.
G <- 0.20

# Means
m1 <- mean(data$A, tr = G)
m2 <- mean(data$B, tr = G)

# Winsorized Variances
var1 <- winvar(data$A, tr = G)
var2 <- winvar(data$B, tr = G)

# Observations left after trimming
h1 <- n1 - 2 * floor(G * n1)
h2 <- n2 - 2 * floor(G * n2)

# Squared Standard Error
d1 <- ((n1 - 1) * var1) / (h1 * (h1 - 1))
d2 <- ((n2 - 1) * var2) / (h2 * (h2 - 1))

# Degrees of Freedom
df <- ((d1 + d2)^2) /
  (((d1^2) / (h1 - 1)) + ((d2^2) / (h2 - 1)))

# Test Statistic
mu <- 0
diff <- m1 - m2
t_stat <- (diff - mu) / sqrt(d1 + d2)

# p-value
p <- pt(abs(t_stat), df = df, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2

# Confidence Interval
alpha <- 0.05
t_crit <- abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df))

CI_bot <- diff - t_crit * sqrt(d1 + d2)
CI_top <- diff + t_crit * sqrt(d1 + d2)
CI <- paste("[", round(CI_bot, 3),
  ", ", round(CI_top, 3),
  "]",
  sep = ""
)
## T = -8.642
## df = 198.1408
## p = 1.845119e-15
## CI = [-2.657, -1.67]
plot_data <- data_AB |>
  group_by(Group) |>
  summarise(
    n = length(Score),
    G = 0.20,
    m = mean(Score, tr = G),
    s = sqrt(winvar(Score, tr = G)),
    se = s / ((1 - 2 * G) * sqrt(n)),
    h = n - 2 * floor(G * n),
    df = h - 1,
    alpha = 0.05,
    t_crit = abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df)),
    moe = t_crit * se
  )


# Plot
ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = Group, y = m)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", colour = "black", aes(fill = Group)) +
  geom_errorbar(
    aes(
      ymin = m - moe,
      ymax = m + moe
    ),
    width = 0.25
  ) +
  xlab("Group") +
  ylab("Score")

Question 12.

Your friend Bertrand scores a 66 in their philosophy class. What percentile does this put them at? Assume the class marks are normally distributed with a mean of 79.6 and a standard deviation of 12.95.

Click for Solution

Two ways to solve this:

Option 1:

pnorm(66, mean = 79.6, sd = 12.95) * 100
## [1] 14.68147


Option 2:

z <- (66 - 79.6)/12.95
pnorm(z, mean = 0, sd = 1) * 100
## [1] 14.68147



Question 13.

From the previous question, how many standard deviations above or below the mean are they?

Click for Solution 
z <- (66 - 79.6) / 12.95
z
## [1] -1.050193

They are 1.05 standard deviations below the mean.



Question 14.

Your other friend (Jimbo) is 0.98 standard deviations below the mean in their philosophy class. What percentile does this put them at? Assume the class marks are normally distributed with a mean of 79.6 and a standard deviation of 12.95.

Click for Solution 
pnorm(-0.98, mean = 0, sd = 1) * 100
## [1] 16.35431



Question 15.

From the previous question, what percentage of students scored higher than your friend Jimbo?

Click for Solution

Two ways to solve this:

Option 1:

(1 - pnorm(-0.98, mean = 0, sd = 1)) * 100
## [1] 83.64569


Option 2:

pnorm(-0.98, mean = 0, sd = 1, lower.tail = FALSE) * 100
## [1] 83.64569
